tenderness. A CT scan is arranged and a representative slice is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the changes seen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pyonephrosis","Diverticulitis","Appendicitis","Iliac artery aneurysm","Retroperitoneal haematoma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan reveals a large, fluid-filled cavity located behind the bladder and in front of the rectum, containing a pocket of air. This is indicative of a well-walled-off abscess. The most likely cause of this abscess is \u003Cstrong\u003Ediverticulitis\u003C/strong\u003E, which can lead to the formation of a pericolic abscess due to perforation and subsequent bacterial infection. The presence of gas within the abscess is consistent with bacterial activity, commonly seen in diverticulitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyonephrosis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to pus in the renal collecting system, typically associated with an obstructed and infected kidney. It would not present as a pelvic abscess with gas formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAppendicitis\u003C/strong\u003E can lead to abscess formation, but it is less common for an appendiceal abscess to present in the pelvis with gas unless there is a significant perforation and spread, which is less likely in this age group without prior symptoms of appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIliac artery aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E would present as a vascular mass and is unlikely to contain gas or present as an abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERetroperitoneal haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E would present as a collection of blood, not gas, and would not typically form a walled-off abscess with air pockets.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acute diverticulitis is often complicated by pericolic abscess formation.","Diverticulitis can lead to the formation of gas-containing abscesses due to bacterial activity."],"references":["Stollman N, Smalley W, Hirano I; AGA Institute Clinical Guidelines Committee. American Gastroenterological Association Institute Guideline on the Management of Acute Diverticulitis. Gastroenterology. 2015 Dec;149(7):1944-9. doi: 10.1053/j.gastro.2015.10.003. Epub 2015 Oct 8. PMID: 26453777. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26453777/","Minordi LM, Larosa L, Berte G, Pecere S, Manfredi R. CT of the acute colonic diverticulitis: a pictorial essay. Diagn Interv Radiol. 2020 Nov;26(6):546-551. doi: 10.5152/dir.2020.19645. PMID: 33180020; PMCID: PMC7664754. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33180020/","Tiralongo F, Di Pietro S, Milazzo D, Galioto S, Castiglione DG, Ini\u0027 C, Foti PV, Mosconi C, Giurazza F, Venturini M, Zanghi\u0027 GN, Palmucci S, Basile A. Acute Colonic Diverticulitis: CT Findings, Classifications, and a Proposal of a Structured Reporting Template. Diagnostics (Basel). 2023 Dec 8;13(24):3628. doi: 10.3390/diagnostics13243628. PMID: 38132212; PMCID: PMC10742435. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38132212/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68348"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1635"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19850"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20431"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19850"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e4868ae0-7a0e-4682-8245-60366411fcbd.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e4868ae0-7a0e-4682-8245-60366411fcbd.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":413,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"20431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20431"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SxIL74RS6kIUOugSDVpwJc09mI6QT0.jpg","th